                <h5>Diamond Alternatives</h5>
                <p>Over the years, a number of other stones have been used in jewellery in place of diamonds. These stones, known as diamond alternatives or diamond simulants, look like diamonds, but they’re not the same. They may have similar physical features, but the chemical compositions of these alternatives are completely different. To understand what’s real and what’s fake, let’s take a closer look at the various diamond simulants that are popular today.</p>
                <h5>Cubic Zirconia</h5>
                <p>These stones, which are also known as American Diamonds or simply CZ, are probably the most commonly used diamond alternative. The stone is created by artificially producing a version of the element zircon. These stones are chemically completely different from diamonds. They are not as hard and the sparkle isn’t quite as brilliant. Since these stones aren’t found in nature, they are not considered gemstones.
                </p>
                <h5>Moissanite</h5>
                <p>This diamond alternative started off as a naturally-occurring mineral. But the natural supply available wasn’t enough to embellish even small pieces of jewellery, so scientists found a way to create the mineral in laboratories. The stones created are said to have a lot of fire. This means that when light hits the stone, you can see a rainbow effect. The stones are quite hard but are more likely to get scratched than diamonds. While most moissanite stones are colourless, over time the colour may change, which means that the colour of these stones does not hold up quite as well as that of diamonds.</p>
